Introduction

Framing the Problem

This notebook's goal is to imitate common practice for Deep Learning Engineers. I will take an exisiting model, and use it for this particular lab's requirements.

  • This lab will involve the Dog vs. Cats competition image dataset from the class notebook.
  • After this intoduction, I will explore the data, such as the number of files split between the training, test and validation folders, image dimensions, etc
  • After Data Exploration, I will train two network models, one neural network, and another VGG16
  • I will evaluate the preformance of the best model for each network. I'll look into the accuracy, confusion metric, precision, recall, F1-score, precision-recall curve for each model.
  • I will explore the specific examples in which the models failed to predict correctly.

The dataset contains 25,000 unique images of both dogs and cats. I have reduced the dataset to 2000 images for training, 1000 for testing, and 2000 for validation.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# Function to count the number of files in a dataset
def count_files(dataset):
    count = 0
    for _ in dataset.unbatch():
        count += 1
    return count

# Get the number of files in each dataset
train_files = count_files(train_dataset)
validation_files = count_files(validation_dataset)
test_files = count_files(test_dataset)

# Plot the number of files using a bar chart
datasets = ['Train', 'Validation', 'Test']
file_counts = [train_files, validation_files, test_files]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(datasets, file_counts, color=['blue', 'orange', 'green'])
plt.title('Number of Files in Each Dataset')
plt.xlabel('Dataset')
plt.ylabel('Number of Files')
plt.show()

import os
from PIL import Image

# Assuming the dataset is organized in directories for each class
data_dir = "data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/train"
classes = ["cat", "dog"]

# Function to get image dimensions
def get_image_dimensions(directory, classes):
    widths = []
    heights = []
    for cls in classes:
        class_dir = os.path.join(directory, cls)
        for filename in os.listdir(class_dir):
            if filename.endswith(".jpg"):
                with Image.open(os.path.join(class_dir, filename)) as img:
                    widths.append(img.width)
                    heights.append(img.height)
    return widths, heights

# Get image dimensions
widths, heights = get_image_dimensions(data_dir, classes)

# Plot the image dimensions
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(widths, heights, alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Image Dimensions')
plt.xlabel('Width (pixels)')
plt.ylabel('Height (pixels)')
plt.show()

In[6]:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint

# Define the neural network
def create_neural_network_model():
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
    x = data_augmentation(inputs)
    x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.Flatten()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
    outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
    model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
    return model

data_augmentation = keras.Sequential(
    [
        layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
        layers.RandomRotation(0.1),
        layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
    ]
)

model = create_neural_network_model()
model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy",
              optimizer="rmsprop",
              metrics=["accuracy"])

callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="./models/convnet_from_scratch.keras",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss")
]
history = model.fit(
    train_dataset,
    epochs=30,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,
    callbacks=callbacks)

In[8]:
conv_base = keras.applications.vgg16.VGG16(
    weights="imagenet",
    include_top=False,
    input_shape=(180, 180, 3))

def get_features_and_labels(dataset):
    all_features = []
    all_labels = []
    for images, labels in dataset:
        preprocessed_images = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(images)
        features = conv_base.predict(preprocessed_images)
        all_features.append(features)
        all_labels.append(labels)
    return np.concatenate(all_features), np.concatenate(all_labels)

train_features, train_labels =  get_features_and_labels(train_dataset)
val_features, val_labels =  get_features_and_labels(validation_dataset)
test_features, test_labels =  get_features_and_labels(test_dataset)

# Identify misclassified examples
misclassified_indices = np.where(y_true != y_pred_classes)[0]

def plot_misclassified_examples(dataset, misclassified_indices, y_true, y_pred_classes):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
    for i, idx in enumerate(misclassified_indices[:9]):  # Plot up to 9 misclassified examples
        plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)
        img = dataset.unbatch().skip(idx).take(1)
        for image, label in img:
            plt.imshow(image.numpy().astype("uint8"))
            plt.title(f"True: {int(y_true[idx])}, Pred: {int(y_pred_classes[idx])}")
            plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

# Plot misclassified examples
plot_misclassified_examples(test_dataset, misclassified_indices, y_true, y_pred_classes)

Conclusion

Neural Network

Neural Network Recap:

  • Test Accuracy: 0.7865
  • Confusion Matrix:
    [[471, 529],
    [464, 536]]
  • Precision: 0.48 for both the classes
  • Recall: 0.45 for Cat, 0.52 for Dog
  • F1-Score: 0.47 for Cat, 0.50 for Dog
  • Overall Accuracy: 0.48
  • PR AUC: 0.49

Neural Network Summary:

  • The neural network model shows a moderate performance with accuracy of 0.7865.
  • The confusion matrix indicates that the model has a balanced but relatively low precision and recall for both classes, which is verified through the classification report.
  • The F1-scores suggest that the model struggles to balance the precision and recall, indicating room for improvement in distinguishing between cats and dogs.
  • The PR AUC of 0.49 indicates that the model's predicitons are not much better compared to completely random guesses.

VGG16 Network

VGG16 Network Recap:

  • Test Accuracy: 0.973
  • Confusion Matrix:
    [[983, 17],
    [38, 962]]
  • Precision: 0.983
  • Recall: 0.962
  • F1-Score: 0.972
  • PR AUC: 0.986

VGG16 Network Summary:

  • The VGG16 model significantly outperforms the custom neural network with a much higher accuracy of 0.973.
  • The confusion matrix shows that the model correctly classifies most instances, with very few misclassifications, more data to train the model could improve this.
  • High precision and recall values indicate that the model is very effective at distinguishing between cats and dogs.
  • The F1-score of 0.972 suggests a balance between precision and recall, making this model highly reliable.
  • The PR AUC of 0.986 means that the model is very accurate in predictions, and is nearly perfect, with some minor misses.

In conclusion, the higher preforming model in this analysis is the VGG16 model, which is the more dominant model in all of the evaluation tasks.
